05140nam a22009135i 9780823245598DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232455987 a10.1515/97808232455982doi  a(DE-B1597)555040  a(OCoLC)923764049  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE743.5b.V44 2013 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a973.9212231 aVégső, Roland, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Naked Communist :bCold War Modernism and the Politics of Popular Culture /cRoland Végső. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Aesthetic Unconscious -- t2. Anti-Communist Politics and the Limits of Representation -- t3. The Enemy, the Secret, and the Catastrophe -- t4. Anti-Communist Aesthetic Ideology -- t5. One World: Nuclear Holocausts -- t6. Two Worlds: Stolen Secrets -- t7. Three Worlds: Global Enemies -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Naked Communist argues that the political ideologies of modernity were fundamentally determined by four basic figures: the world, the enemy, the secret, and the catastrophe. While the "world" names the totality that functioned as the ultimate horizon of modern political imagination, the three other figures define the necessary limits of this totality by reflecting on the limits of representation.The book highlights the enduring presence of these figures in the modern imagination through detailed analysis of a concrete historical example: American anti-Communist politics of the 1950s. Its primary objective is to describe the internal mechanisms of what we could call an anti- Communist "aesthetic ideology." The book thus traces the way anti-Communist popular culture emerged in the discourse of Cold War liberalism as a political symptom of modernism. Based on a discursive analysis of American anti-Communist politics, the book presents parallel readings of modernism and popular fiction from the 1950s (nuclear holocaust novels, spy novels, and popular political novels) in order to show that, despite the radical separation of the two cultural fields, they both participated in a common ideological program.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAestheticsxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAnti-communist movements in literature. 0aAnti-communist movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aAnti-communist movementszUnited StatesxPhilosophy. 0aAtomic bomb in literature. 0aCold War in literature. 0aCold WarxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aModernism (Literature)zUnited States. 0aNineteen fifties. 0aPolitical fiction, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitics and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPopular culturexPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPropaganda, Anti-communistzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSpy stories, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 4aAesthetic Ideology. 4aAnti-Communism. 4aCatastrophe. 4aCold War. 4aEnemy. 4aModernism. 4aPopular fiction. 4aSecrecy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823245598zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823245598423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823245598.jpg  a978-3-11-070729-8  FUP eBook-Package Backli